EXTRACTION_ORCHESTRATOR_V2
Status: Locked for implementation drafting
Purpose: Deterministic orchestration from NTI source document -> REC -> AU split -> lane-specific canonical gates.

--------------------------------------------------
I. ROLE
--------------------------------------------------

The Extraction Orchestrator is the deterministic execution bridge between NTI intake material and the existing lane-specific canonicalization gates.

It is responsible for:

1. accepting one normalized NTI source document
2. producing one REC from raw source text
3. splitting that REC into atomic units
4. routing atomic units into the pressure lane and narrative lane
5. invoking the correct pre-canonical mappers/gates in the correct order
6. returning a fully auditable stage bundle

It is NOT responsible for:

- search
- packet enumeration
- packet loading
- packet writing
- freeform inference
- semantic compression
- subclass invention
- pressure reinterpretation
- canonical ID strategy definition
- cross-run dedup policy
- registry mutation semantics beyond returning outputs to caller

--------------------------------------------------
II. INPUT CONTRACT
--------------------------------------------------

The orchestrator accepts exactly one NTI source document.

Input shape:

NtiSourceDocument {
  sourceId: string
  sourceType: "harvest_packet"
  seasonWindow: string
  title: string
  publication: string
  author: string
  url: string
  rawText: string
  teamContext: string[]
  narrativeTags: string[]
}

Input invariants:

- sourceId must be non-empty
- rawText must be non-empty
- rawText must already be cleaned prose
- rawText must not be HTML / JS / navigation residue
- one source document only per invocation
- no batching in V2

--------------------------------------------------
III. OUTPUT CONTRACT
--------------------------------------------------

The orchestrator returns one deterministic result bundle.

ExtractionOrchestratorResult {
  sourceId: string
  sourceReference: string

  rec: dict | null

  atomicUnits: list[dict]
  pcrs: list[dict]
  splitRejections: list[dict]

  pressureLane: {
    ploRecords: list[dict]
    cpsObjects: list[dict]
    cpsRejections: list[dict]
    cpsAudit: list[dict]
  }

  narrativeLane: {
    ncaInputs: list[dict]
    ncaAccepted: list[dict]
    ncaRejected: list[dict]
    santaInputs: list[dict]
    csnObjects: list[dict]
    csnRejections: list[dict]
  }

  stageStatus: {
    recProduced: boolean
    splitExecuted: boolean
    pressureLaneExecuted: boolean
    narrativeLaneExecuted: boolean
  }
}

Output invariants:

- all fields always present
- empty arrays, not omitted arrays
- no silent stage drops
- stage-local failure must be visible in structured output

--------------------------------------------------
IV. SOURCE REFERENCE RULE
--------------------------------------------------

V2 source reference rule:

sourceReference = sourceId

This sourceReference is passed to:

- split_rec(...)
- enforce_plo_e(...)
- narrative event candidates
- SANTA event inputs

No alternate source reference derivation permitted in V2.

--------------------------------------------------
V. STAGE ORDER (LOCKED)
--------------------------------------------------

Exact order:

1. produce_rec(rawText, is_composite=False)
2. split_rec(rec, sourceReference)

Pressure lane:
3P. map AUs through enforce_plo_e(...)
4P. send resulting plo_record(s) to enforce_psta(...)

Narrative lane:
3N. build event candidates from AUs
4N. run enforce_nca(event)
5N. if classification == "CSN", run enforce_santa(event_with_nca_result)

No reordering allowed.

--------------------------------------------------
VI. STAGE 1 — REC PRODUCTION
--------------------------------------------------

Callable:
produce_rec(text: str, is_composite: bool = False) -> dict

Invocation:
produce_rec(rawText, False)

Rules:

- rawText passed exactly as received
- no pre-summarization
- no chunking
- no rewriting

Failure behavior:

- if REC production fails:
  - rec = null
  - downstream arrays empty
  - stageStatus.recProduced = false
  - no later stages execute

--------------------------------------------------
VII. STAGE 2 — REC SPLIT
--------------------------------------------------

Callable:
split_rec(rec: dict, source_reference: str) -> tuple[list[dict], list[dict], list[dict]]

Invocation:
split_rec(rec, sourceReference)

Outputs:

- atomicUnits = first tuple element
- pcrs = second tuple element
- splitRejections = third tuple element

Rules:

- split called exactly once per successful REC
- all three outputs preserved
- PCRs preserved but not used in pressure mint path in V2

Failure behavior:

- rec preserved
- atomicUnits = []
- pcrs = []
- splitRejections contains structured split failure
- no lane stages execute

--------------------------------------------------
VIII. PRESSURE LANE — GROUND TRUTH
--------------------------------------------------

V2 pressure lane is:

AUs
-> enforce_plo_e(...)
-> plo_record
-> enforce_psta(...)

Important lock:

PSTA does NOT consume AUs directly.
PSTA does NOT consume PCRs directly.
PSTA consumes plo_record["observations"]-style input through a full PLO record.

This matches the implemented pressure mint expectations and the PSTA contract, which requires validated PLO-E style input and is post-critic / canonicalization-only. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}

--------------------------------------------------
IX. PRESSURE LANE — PLO MAPPING
--------------------------------------------------

Known upstream mapper:
enforce_plo_e(au, observations, source_reference)

V2 rule:

- each eligible AU may be passed into enforce_plo_e(...)
- orchestrator must preserve resulting plo_record(s)
- no custom AU->PLO field invention outside the known mapper
- PCRs are not used as PSTA inputs in V2

SourceSeedText rule:

- sourceSeedText derives from AU text through the existing PLO-E path, not from orchestrator invention

Observation rule:

- plo_record must include observations shaped for PSTA consumption
- orchestrator does not handcraft PSTA observation dicts if enforce_plo_e already provides the path

--------------------------------------------------
X. PRESSURE LANE — PSTA EXECUTION
--------------------------------------------------

Callable:
enforce_psta(plo_record, enum_registry_version=...)

Grounded PSTA input facts:

- top-level sourceSeedText is optional/fallback
- practical requirement is that plo_record.observations contain dicts with fields such as:
  signalClass
  environment
  pressureSignalDomain
  pressureVector
  signalPolarity
  observationSource
  castRequirement
  tier
  observation

PSTA failure conditions include:
- duplicate canonical IDs
- CPS schema invalid
- enum/schema violations

This is consistent with the PSTA contract: PSTA is transformational / identity-minting only, post-critic, and must receive validated pressure-legible observation style input rather than raw extracted material. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}

V2 execution rule:

- invoke enforce_psta once per produced plo_record
- preserve canonical CPS objects
- preserve rejections
- preserve audit output
- one failed plo_record does not halt remaining pressure lane records

--------------------------------------------------
XI. NARRATIVE LANE — GROUND TRUTH
--------------------------------------------------

V2 narrative lane is:

AUs
-> build event candidate
-> enforce_nca(event)
-> if classification == "CSN"
-> enforce_santa(event_with_nca_result)

Important lock:

SANTA is not a classifier.
SANTA accepts only CSN-classified inputs from NCA, consistent with its contract. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

--------------------------------------------------
XII. NARRATIVE LANE — EVENT CANDIDATE CONSTRUCTION
--------------------------------------------------

V2 event candidate construction rule:

- build event candidates from AUs only
- one AU may yield zero or one event candidate
- no multi-AU synthetic event composition in V2

Minimum event candidate base:

EventCandidate {
  eventDescription: <AU text or deterministic event text derived from AU>
  sourceReference: <sourceReference>
  timestampContext: <deterministic metadata-derived value or fallback non-empty placeholder>
  actorRole: <optional>
  action: <optional>
  objectRole: <optional>
  contextRole: <optional>
}

Rules:

- no invented causality
- no multi-observation merging
- timestampContext must be non-empty before SANTA path
- if no reliable timestamp exists, use deterministic fallback policy defined by implementation, but it must remain stable and non-empty

--------------------------------------------------
XIII. NARRATIVE LANE — NCA EXECUTION
--------------------------------------------------

Callable:
enforce_nca(event)

V2 rule:

- enforce_nca runs first on every event candidate
- if NCA output classification != "CSN", do not send to SANTA
- preserve NCA accepted/rejected outputs separately

Derived-field rule:

- classification and standaloneSubclass used by SANTA come from NCA output, not orchestrator invention

--------------------------------------------------
XIV. NARRATIVE LANE — SANTA EXECUTION
--------------------------------------------------

Callable:
enforce_santa(event)

Grounded SANTA input facts:

Required:
- classification == "CSN"
- standaloneSubclass valid
- eventDescription non-empty string
- sourceReference string
- timestampContext non-empty string

Optional / nullable:
- actorRole
- action
- objectRole
- contextRole

SANTA rejects:
- non-CSN inputs
- invalid/missing subclass
- invalid/missing eventDescription
- invalid/missing sourceReference
- invalid/missing timestampContext
- invalid identity field types
- schema-invalid canonical output

This matches the SANTA contract: SANTA receives CSN-classified input, canonicalizes only, does not classify or mutate meaning, and performs deterministic canonical archival normalization. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

V2 execution rule:

- merge NCA-derived classification + standaloneSubclass into event candidate
- invoke enforce_santa only when classification == "CSN"
- preserve canonical CSN objects
- preserve SANTA rejections
- one failed event does not halt remaining narrative lane events

--------------------------------------------------
XV. DETERMINISM RULES
--------------------------------------------------

The orchestrator must be deterministic.

Given the same NTI source document, it must:

- call the same functions in the same order
- derive the same sourceReference
- produce the same event candidate inputs
- produce the same lane inputs
- produce the same structured result bundle shape

Prohibited:

- randomness
- time-based branching
- global mutable counters
- opportunistic fallback variation
- hidden state lookup

--------------------------------------------------
XVI. NO-INFERENCE RULES
--------------------------------------------------

The orchestrator may not:

- summarize source material
- invent pressure semantics
- invent narrative subclass
- merge AUs into broader claims
- fill missing canonical fields with guessed content
- reinterpret non-CSN material as CSN

The orchestrator may:

- map fields deterministically
- invoke existing lane mappers/gates
- preserve outputs
- return structured diagnostics

--------------------------------------------------
XVII. FAILURE POLICY
--------------------------------------------------

Hard stop conditions:

- invalid NTI input
- REC production failure
- split failure severe enough to produce no usable AUs

Soft failure conditions:

- one AU fails PLO mapping
- one plo_record fails PSTA
- one event fails NCA
- one CSN candidate fails SANTA

Soft failures must be recorded without halting the full document.

--------------------------------------------------
XVIII. NON-GOALS
--------------------------------------------------

V2 does not include:

- PSCA integration
- full live pressure lane eligibility verification upstream of PSTA
- CME lane
- batch execution
- replay suppression
- registry commit semantics
- cross-document reconciliation
- advanced timestamp recovery
- narrative importance weighting

--------------------------------------------------
XIX. ACCEPTANCE TEST
--------------------------------------------------

Step A is complete when the following is true:

Given one NTI source document from shared-corpus, the orchestrator can deterministically:

1. produce one REC
2. split it into AUs / PCRs / split rejections
3. route AUs into the pressure lane through enforce_plo_e -> enforce_psta
4. route AUs into the narrative lane through enforce_nca -> enforce_santa
5. return a structured result bundle with preserved canonical outputs and preserved rejections
6. perform no freeform inference and no dead-branch routing